    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation in your legs during HIIT sprints is a classic case of lactic acid buildup, a phenomenon that's often referred to as \"the burn.\" It's a natural response to intense exercise, where your muscles break down carbohydrates to produce energy, releasing lactic acid as a byproduct. This acid accumulates in your muscles, causing the characteristic burning or fatigue sensation.\n\nAs you continue to exercise, your body's anaerobic system kicks in, relying on stored glycogen and ATP to fuel your muscles. However, this process is limited, and eventually, your body starts to break down muscle tissue to release more energy, leading to an even greater accumulation of lactic acid.\n\nTo get rid of lactic acid, your body relies on the aerobic system, which kicks in after you've stopped exercising. During this phase, your heart rate slows down, and your body starts to transport the lactic acid from your muscles to your liver, where it's converted back into glucose and stored for later use. It's a bit like a \"goblin's getaway\" – the lactic acid has to escape the muscles before it can be processed and cleared out.",
      "source": "target",
